🧠 📱 STORY: “A USER BUYS A PRODUCT ON AN ANDROID APP”

We’ll follow:
User → Android App → OS → Network → Backend

🎬 SCENE 1: USER OPENS THE APP
Flow:
User taps app icon
→ Android launches Activity
→ App process starts (new UID)

🧩 Component: Activity (Application Layer)
What it does:
. Entry point (UI screen)
. Handles user interaction

🔐 Security happening here:
App runs in its own sandbox (UID)

👉 Enforced by Linux kernel

💣 Threat: Malicious App tries to launch your Activity
Q. How?
-> If your Activity is:
android:exported="true"
Another app can do:
Intent → launch your Activity

Q. Why this is dangerous?
-> Attacker bypasses your UI flow
Example:
. Opens payment screen directly
. Skips login

🛡️ Mitigation
-> android:exported="false"
-> Use explicit intents
-> Validate all incoming data

🎬 SCENE 2: LOGIN FLOW
Flow:
User enters username/password
→ App sends HTTPS request
→ Backend returns JWT token
→ App stores token

🧩 Components involved
Activity (UI)
Android Keystore (secure storage)
Network stack (TLS)

🔐 What SHOULD happen?
Token stored securely using hardware-backed keystore

💣 Threat: Token Theft
Q. Where it happens?
SharedPreferences (plaintext storage)

Q. Why it happens?
Developer convenience

Q. Attack?
Rooted device → attacker reads app storage
Backup extraction → token leak

🛡️ Mitigation
-> Use EncryptedSharedPreferences
-> Use hardware-backed keystore
-> Avoid storing long-lived tokens

🎬 SCENE 3: INTER-APP COMMUNICATION (HIDDEN ENTRY POINT)
Flow:
Another app sends Intent → your app

🧩 Component: Intent + Binder IPC

🔐 What Android allows:
Apps can communicate freely via Intents

💣 Threat: Intent Injection
Real example
Intent:
action=TRANSFER_MONEY
amount=10000

Attacker app sends this to your app.

Q. Why it works?
Your app trusts incoming intent blindly

🛡️ Mitigation
Check:
- Caller identity (UID)
- Validate all fields
- Require permissions

🎬 SCENE 4: PERMISSION SYSTEM (FRAMEWORK LAYER)
Flow:
App requests:
READ_CONTACTS
ACCESS_LOCATION

🧩 Component: Android Framework

🔐 What it does
Enforces runtime permissions

💣 Threat: Permission Misuse
Q. Why it happens?
User clicks "Allow" without understanding

Q. Attack
App:
Reads contacts → sends to server

🛡️ Mitigation:
-> Request minimal permissions
-> Explain why permission is needed
-> Check permission before use

🎬 SCENE 5: CONFUSED DEPUTY (VERY IMPORTANT)
Flow:
App A (attacker) → calls your app
Your app → accesses sensitive resource

🧩 Component: Binder IPC + Framework

💣 Threat: Confused Deputy
Real scenario
Your app has:
READ_SMS permission
Attacker app:
→ sends request to your app
→ your app reads SMS
→ returns data

Q. Why this happens?
-> Your app trusts caller

🛡️ Mitigation
Check:
Binder.getCallingUid()
Enforce:
Caller must have permission too

🎬 SCENE 6: ANDROID RUNTIME (ART)
Flow:
App code executes (Java/Kotlin → ART)

🧩 Component: ART

🔐 What it does?
-> Executes bytecode
-> Manages memory

💣 Threat: Native Code Exploits
Q. Where?
JNI (C/C++ libraries)
Q. Why?
No memory safety (buffer overflow)

🛡️ Mitigation
-> Avoid native code unless necessary
-> Use safe libraries

🎬 SCENE 7: KERNEL (REAL SECURITY ENFORCER)
Flow:
App tries to:
- access file
- use camera
- talk to another app

🧩 Component: Linux Kernel

🔐 What it enforces
1. App Sandbox
Each app = unique UID
2. SELinux
Strict access rules

💣 Threat: Privilege Escalation
Q. How?
Exploit kernel bug → gain root
Q. Why dangerous?
Kernel = highest privilege

🛡️ Mitigation
-> OS updates
-> SELinux enforcing
-> Avoid rooted devices (detect root)

🎬 SCENE 8: HARDWARE KEYSTORE (ROOT OF TRUST)
Flow:
App stores encryption key
→ goes to hardware keystore

🧩 Component: TEE / Secure Element

🔐 What it does
Keys never leave hardware

💣 Threat: Software key extraction
Q. Why?
If key stored in app memory → extractable

🛡️ Mitigation
-> Use hardware-backed keys
-> Perform crypto inside TEE

🎬 SCENE 9: NETWORK CALL (END-TO-END FLOW)
Flow:
App → HTTPS → Backend

🔐 Security
-> TLS encryption
-> Certificate validation

💣 Threat: MITM
Q. How?
User installs malicious certificate
Q. Why?
App trusts system CA store

🛡️ Mitigation
Certificate pinning


🧠 FULL END-TO-END ATTACK CHAIN (REALISTIC)
1. Attacker installs malicious app
2. Sends crafted Intent → your exported Activity
3. Bypasses authentication
4. Extracts token from insecure storage
5. Uses MITM to intercept traffic
6. Exploits backend APIs
7. If rooted → reads memory / storage
8. Gains full account access
